Where am I? Your first commands.

Here are five tiny commands that answer the two most basic questions: who am I, and where am I. Every one of them takes no arguments at all. You just type the name and hit Enter.

The first is whoami, spelled who-a-m-i, all one word. It prints your username. That's surprisingly useful once you start switching between accounts and lose track.

The second is hostname, which prints the name of the machine you're on.

The third is p-w-d, which stands for print working directory. It tells you exactly where you are in the filesystem right now.

The fourth is date, which prints the system's current date and time.

And the fifth is uname, spelled u-name, with the dash-a flag. That prints information about the kernel. The dash-a just means give me all of it.

Think of these as your orientation tools. Any time you're not sure who you are or where you are, maybe after connecting over S-S-H, or after switching users with sudo, or after a change-directory you're not certain worked, whoami and p-w-d are the two commands you'll reach for without even thinking.
